<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-208-436  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 208 436.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Learning  April 1989 v8 n6 p36(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Computer viruses: an epidemic real or imagined?andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Chaffin, Ellen.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Computer viruses are programs, or routines within programs, thathave gone askew.andP;  They are synthetic mutations that take advantageof the weaknesses of a computer system and create programs thatspread.andP;  There are two categories: benign and malicious.andP;  Benignviruses are usually harmless.andP;  For instance, on Dec 1987 themessage 'Peace on Earth' appeared on Macintosh screens.andP;  Maliciousviruses often cause irreparable damage.andP;  The two most common typesare worms and trojan horses.andP;  A worm takes up increasingly moredisk and-or memory space.andP;  The trojan horse disguises itself as autility or enhancement, but then does something entirelydifferent.andP;  The majority of viruses come from bulletin boards,shareware, and public domain software.andP;  The best preventativeefforts are frequent backup of hard disks, never download directlyto a network, and thoroughly check all software before putting iton the network.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     EducationComputer virusesSecurity SoftwareImpact Analysis.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Rx for health (tips on protecting against viruses). (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>